they are i18n translation messages for using inside:
```ts nuxt-template/i18n.config.ts
import messages from './locales/messages'

export default defineI18nConfig(() => ({
  messages: messages,
}))
```


For proper typing of i18n translation messages, you should define the type structure that matches your translation objects. Here's how you can type these files:

First, create a type definition for the message structure (you can put this in a separate types file or at the top of `messages.ts`):

```typescript
type Messages = {
  localeAlert?: string;
  layout: {
    nav: {
      about: string;
      contact: string;
      continue?: string;
      blog: string;
    };
    general?: {
      actions: {
        confirm: string;
        cancel: string;
      };
    };
  };
  general?: {
    actions: {
      confirm: string;
      cancel: string;
      continue: string;
    };
  };
  landing: {
    hero: {
      title: string;
      description: string;
      links: {
        whatsNew: string;
        getStarted: string;
        learnMore: string;
      };
    };
    features: {
      one: {
        title: string;
        description: string;
      };
      two: {
        title: string;
        description: string;
      };
      three: {
        title: string;
        description: string;
      };
      four: {
        title: string;
        description: string;
      };
    };
    faq: {
      title: string;
      questions: {
        one: {
          label: string;
          content: string;
        };
        two: {
          label: string;
          content: string;
        };
        three: {
          label: string;
          content: string;
        };
      };
    };
  };
}

// In messages.ts
export default {
  en,
  de,
} as Record<string, Messages>

// In en.ts and de.ts
export default {
  // ... your translations
} satisfies Messages
```

This type structure ensures that:
1. All translation files follow the same structure
2. Optional fields are marked with `?` since some translations might not have all fields
3. The main messages object is typed as a record of language codes to message structures
4. Using `satisfies` keyword allows for type checking while maintaining the literal type information

When used with `defineI18nConfig`, TypeScript will properly type-check your translation messages.
