Yes, you can use the types from `vue-i18n`. The most relevant type for your messages would be `DefaultLocaleMessageSchema` or you could define your own schema. Here's how you can type your files:

```typescript
// locales/messages.ts
import type { DefaultLocaleMessageSchema } from 'vue-i18n'
import de from './de'
import en from './en'

export default {
  en,
  de,
} satisfies Record<string, DefaultLocaleMessageSchema>

// locales/en.ts and locales/de.ts
export default {
  // ... your translations
} satisfies DefaultLocaleMessageSchema
```

Alternatively, if you want to be more specific with your schema:

```typescript
import type { LocaleMessageDictionary } from 'vue-i18n'

export default {
  en,
  de,
} satisfies Record<string, LocaleMessageDictionary>
```

These types will integrate well with the `defineI18nConfig` function and provide proper type checking for your i18n setup.
